  "analysis_markdown": "## Local Diff Analysis\n\nAdded HTTP API server support to Silverforge Factory CLI using FastAPI and uvicorn. Introduces a new `serve` command that starts an HTTP server with configurable host/port, plus a `/hello` endpoint returning a simple JSON greeting. Includes port validation (0-65535 range) and test coverage for both CLI command and server endpoints. FastAPI and uvicorn are now hard dependencies in pyproject.toml.\n\n### Suggested Review Focus\n- Port validation logic: Port range check (0-65535) is correct but doesn't validate if the port is actually available on the system. Reviewers should confirm if port conflicts should be caught by uvicorn or handled in the CLI.\n- Dependency management strategy: FastAPI and uvicorn added as hard dependencies rather than optional. Verify this aligns with project goals—increases base package size even for users who don't need the API.\n- Test coverage gaps: Three tests in test_cli_serve.py are empty placeholders (port 0, port 65535, defaults). These need implementation or justification for why they're skipped.\n- Security implications: The `/hello` endpoint is unauthenticated and accessible to any client. Confirm if this is intentional or if authentication/CORS policies should be added for future endpoints.\n- CLI/server integration pattern: Runtime import of `factory.server` inside serve() command works but defers import error detection. Verify if this late binding is intentional or if eager imports would be preferable.\n\n### Trade-offs\n- FastAPI/uvicorn as hard dependencies increases package footprint; users who only use CLI task runner now pay this cost\n- Port validation only checks numeric range, not OS-level availability—port conflicts handled by uvicorn startup error\n- No error recovery in serve() if uvicorn.run() fails; errors surface directly to user\n- Placeholder tests defer verification of valid port cases and default behavior to manual testing\n\n### Affected Modules\n- factory/cli.py — new serve command with port validation\n- factory/server.py — new FastAPI app module with /hello endpoint\n- pyproject.toml — dependency specification\n- tests/ — new test modules for CLI and server\n\n### Call Chain\n- CLI entry: `factory serve [--host HOST] [--port PORT]`\n- → serve() in factory/cli.py validates port range\n- → imports uvicorn and factory.server.app\n- → uvicorn.run(app, host=host, port=port) starts server\n- → FastAPI routes GET /hello\n- → hello() returns {\"message\": \"Hello, World!\"}\n\n### Design Patterns\n- Separation of concerns: CLI layer (factory/cli.py) separate from API layer (factory/server.py)\n- Deferred imports: uvicorn and server app imported inside serve() to avoid startup cost\n- Standard FastAPI endpoint decoration: @app.get(\"/hello\") decorator on handler function\n- CLI option binding: typer.Option for host/port with defaults and help text\n\n### Reviewer Checklist\n- ✓ Port validation: Confirm boundary cases work (port=0 should be allowed per OS conventions for auto-selection; port=65535 should be accepted; negative and >65535 should reject)\n- ✓ Dependency declaration: Verify fastapi>=0.100 and uvicorn>=0.23 are correctly listed and that optional test deps (pytest, httpx) are properly configured\n- ✓ Test completeness: Review empty test placeholders in test_cli_serve.py—should they be implemented, skipped with pytest.skip(), or removed?\n- ✓ Error handling: Check if uvicorn startup errors (port in use, permission denied) are handled gracefully or surfaced clearly to user\n- ✓ FastAPI app design: Confirm factory/server.py is structured to allow future endpoint additions and middleware integration\n- ✓ Security posture: Is unauthenticated /hello endpoint intentional? Will future endpoints require auth? Should CORS be configured?\n- ✓ Import timing: Verify runtime import of factory.server doesn't cause circular dependencies or obscure import errors\n- ✓ CLI command conflicts: Ensure 'serve' command name doesn't conflict with existing commands and fits overall CLI structure\n",
